Romeo and Juliet and Macbeth Sentiment Analysis

Sentiment analysis on Romeo and Juliet

library(tidytext)
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
library(ggplot2)

# Read the Lexicons (for sentiment classification)
nrc <- read.csv("/Users/usraaziz/Desktop/NRC.csv")

# Read romeo and juliet from file
script_path1 <- "/Users/usraaziz/Desktop/filtered_romeo_and_juliet4.txt"
romeo_and_juliet_lines <- tolower(readLines(script_path1, warn = FALSE))

# Create a data frame with the script lines
romeo_and_juliet_df <- data.frame(line = romeo_and_juliet_lines)

# Tokenize the script lines
romeo_and_juliet_df_tokens <- romeo_and_juliet_df %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, line)

# Load the NRC Word-Emotion Association Lexicon
nrc_lexicon <- tidytext::get_sentiments("nrc")

# Join with the NRC lexicon
sentiments1 <- romeo_and_juliet_df_tokens %>%
  inner_join(nrc_lexicon, by = "word") %>%
  count(sentiment)
## Warning in inner_join(., nrc_lexicon, by = "word"): Detected an unexpected many-to-many relationship between `x` and `y`.
## ℹ Row 4 of `x` matches multiple rows in `y`.
## ℹ Row 11919 of `y` matches multiple rows in `x`.
## ℹ If a many-to-many relationship is expected, set `relationship =
##   "many-to-many"` to silence this warning.
# Create a bar plot of sentiment frequencies
ggplot(sentiments1, aes(x = reorder(sentiment, n), y = n, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Sentiment Analysis on Romeo and Juliet",
       x = "Sentiment",
       y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal()

Contribution to sentiment graph for Romeo and Juliet

library(tidytext)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Assuming you have a dataframe named romeo_and_juliet_df with a column named 'line'
document_linesHG <- unnest_tokens(romeo_and_juliet_df, input = line, output = line, token = "sentences")

# If you want to keep the original case (to_lower = FALSE)
document_linesHG <- document_linesHG %>% mutate(line = ifelse(!is.na(line), line, ""))

romeoandJulietWords <- document_linesHG %>% 
  unnest_tokens(output = word, input = line, token = "words")

nrc_word_countsHG <- romeoandJulietWords %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>% 
  count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  ungroup()
## Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
## Warning in inner_join(., get_sentiments("nrc")): Detected an unexpected many-to-many relationship between `x` and `y`.
## ℹ Row 4 of `x` matches multiple rows in `y`.
## ℹ Row 11919 of `y` matches multiple rows in `x`.
## ℹ If a many-to-many relationship is expected, set `relationship =
##   "many-to-many"` to silence this warning.
nrc_word_countsHG %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  top_n(10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(word, n, fill = sentiment)) + 
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) + 
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales = "free_y") + 
  labs(y = "Contribution to sentiment", x = NULL) + 
  coord_flip()
## Selecting by n

Sentiment analysis on Macbeth

# Read Macbeth from file
script_path_macbeth <- "/Users/usraaziz/Desktop/Macbeth.txt"
macbeth_lines <- tolower(readLines(script_path_macbeth, warn = FALSE))

# Create a data frame with the script lines for Macbeth
macbeth_df <- data.frame(line = macbeth_lines)

# Tokenize the script lines for Macbeth
macbeth_df_tokens <- macbeth_df %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, line)

# Join with the NRC lexicon for Macbeth
sentiments_macbeth <- macbeth_df_tokens %>%
  inner_join(nrc_lexicon, by = "word") %>%
  count(sentiment)
